\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\qc\ltrch\loch \f1\fs24\b1\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In the Confederacy there is only one guaranteed way to escape the social class you are born into: becoming a mage. Because of the usefulness and relative rarity of magical talent, every child in every state of the Confederacy is tested for magical ability twice, once at age 13 and a second time at age 19. Testing positively results in the child being removed to the Collegium Arcanus, a school for training those with ability to become mages. The training of mages is difficult and intense and not all who enter the Collegium survive to graduate. Those that do graduate, however, will forever be mages. The most powerful mages tend to get adopted into the Noble Families, if they were not born of such to begin with. Otherwise they become Common Mages.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Other means of social advancement are more limited in scope, such as being granted a knighthood for service. Or a Bourgeoisie family achieving sufficient financial success that they marry into the Gentry or acquire lands of their own through other means and become \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91New Gentry\u8217\'92. Or an artisan becoming sufficiently famous to earn the patronage of a Noble House and being given land and wealth to become a part of the Gentry. Or a Common Mage marrying into a Noble House.  Or a Noble mage marrying into the lower rungs of the Royal Family. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Magic notwithstanding, there is only one other way for a serf to escape into the upper classes, and even it is nigh impossible. They would have to be conscripted to the military and then perform some fantastic act of bravery or feat of arms that earned them a knighthood. Such acts from the common soldiery are so rare as to be nearly unheard of and even should such a thing happen, it may not even be recognized or rewarded.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Downward mobility is also possible beneath the ranks of the Mages. It is possible for a Knight to be stripped of his Knighthood in punishment for failing their duty or committing certain types of crimes. Or for a Gentry family to be stripped of their lands and wealth for committing certain offenses against the Nobility or Royalty or breaking the laws of the Confederacy or state. A Gentry family could fail, losing their wealth over the span of years or even generations to the point that they lose their lands and become Bourgeoisie. They could even fall so far into debt that the family is sold into serfdom to repay their debts. This can, and often does, happen to Bourgeoisie families as well, falling into serfdom through a failure of effort and wisdom. And anyone, even of the Nobility or Mages can become Outcast, though at their heights within the state, death is a far more common punishment for defiance of the law.}
